Title : Mudzi District
Text : '''Mudzi District''' is a [[Districts of Zimbabwe|district]] of [[Mashonaland East Province]], [[Zimbabwe]], in southern Africa.<ref>{{GEOnet2|32FA881E99A53774E0440003BA962ED3|Mudzi District (Approved)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> It is located in the far eastern part of Zimbabwe, and covers {{Convert|4075|sqkm|sqmi|0}}, all of which is communal land.<ref name="Manhokwe">{{Cite|author=Manhokwe, Lucia|year=2010|title=Top down or bottom up? District Development planning in Mudzi District, Zimbabwe|series=Masters thesis|publisher=[[Erasmus University Rotterdam|Erasmus University]]|location=Rotterdam, the Netherlands|url=http://thesis.eur.nl/pub/8606/final_templete_RP_3_corrected.docx}}</ref> As of the 2012 census, the district had a population of 133,252, this is down from the 135,378 of the 2002 census and reflects emigration due to the poverty of the district. It has a single main road, A2, that runs from the town of Mutoko in Mutoko District in the southwest through the district, past the villages of Chifamba, Mudzi, Chingwena, Masarakufa, Nyamuwanga, the town of [[Kotwa, Zimbabwe|Kotwa]], and the village of Muzezuru to the town of [[Nyamapanda]] before entering [[Mozambique]] to the northeast.<ref>{{Cite map|publisher=Surveyor General, Zimbabwe|title=Zimbabwe. Mount Darwin. Sheet SE-36-02|scale=1:250,0000|edition=1981|url=http://eusoils.jrc.it/esdb_archive/EuDASM/africa/images/maps/download/afr_zw3002_13to.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318092749/http://eusoils.jrc.it/esdb_archive/EuDASM/africa/images/maps/download/afr_zw3002_13to.jpg|archivedate=18 March 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite map|publisher=Surveyor General, Zimbabwe|title=Zimbabwe. Mutoko. Sheet SE-36-06|scale=1:250,0000|edition=1991|url=http://eusoils.jrc.it/esdb_archive/EuDASM/africa/images/maps/download/afr_zw3002_15to.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318092825/http://eusoils.jrc.it/esdb_archive/EuDASM/africa/images/maps/download/afr_zw3002_15to.jpg|archivedate=18 March 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Mudzi District Map|publisher=[[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] (OCHA)|url=https://zw.humanitarianresponse.info/sites/zw.humanitarianresponse.info/files/A3_districts_Mudzi.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424050112/https://zw.humanitarianresponse.info/sites/zw.humanitarianresponse.info/files/A3_districts_Mudzi.pdf|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

As of the 2008 delimitation, Mudzi District had seventeen administrative wards formed into three parliamentary constituencies, and one designated growth centre at Kotwa.<ref name="Manhokwe" /> As of 2008 the [[Mudzi West|Mudzi West constituency]] covered the Shanga, Suswe, Mudzi, Musarakufa and Chiunye areas;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mudzi West constituency|year=2011|publisher=Research Department, Parliament of Zimbabwe|url=http://www.parlzim.gov.zw/attachments/article/130/Mudzi%20West.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424060118/http://www.parlzim.gov.zw/attachments/article/130/Mudzi%20West.pdf|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> the Mudzi South constituency covered Katsande, Nyamatawa, Chikwizo, Gozi and Makana areas;<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mudzi South constituency|year=2011|publisher=Research Department, Parliament of Zimbabwe|url=http://www.parlzim.gov.zw/attachments/article/130/Mudzi%20South.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424060212/http://www.parlzim.gov.zw/attachments/article/130/Mudzi%20South.pdf|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> and the Mudzi North constituency covered the Nyamurapa, 
Kondo, Dendera, Kotwa, and Goromonzi areas and the border town of Nyamapanda.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mudzi North constituency|year=2011|publisher=Research Department, Parliament of Zimbabwe|url=http://www.parlzim.gov.zw/attachments/article/130/Mudzi%20North.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424060258/http://www.parlzim.gov.zw/attachments/article/130/Mudzi%20North.pdf|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>  

Rivers in Mudzi District include the [[Mudzi River|Mudzi]] and Rwenya.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Manyukwe, Clemence|title=Forgotten Mudzi Cries Out|date=11 July 2013|newspaper=Financial Gazette|url=http://www.financialgazette.co.zw/forgotten-mudzi-cries-out/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716181142/http://www.financialgazette.co.zw/forgotten-mudzi-cries-out/|archivedate=16 July 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref>

